and read and read.  <br>
<br>
I don't claim to speak with any authority on the subject of religion.  These questions I ask are because I am sincerely curious about the answer.  You will have to forgive me.  My parents raised me away from religion; therfore, I am sure that I do not have the correct &quot;lingo&quot; down.<br>
<br>
I also don't claim to speak with an authority on the subject of anthropology or sociology.  I am hoping that the more educated, articulate, and eloquent members of this board can help me out.  <br>
<br>
With everything that I know about history, society, and culture, I am come to the conclusion that religion is a construction of man for a specific purpose:  call it control, call it keeping anarchy at bay.  I believe that religion was created to keep us more human than animal (if that makes any sense)  Religion gives us rules. <br>
<br>
Because of what I have been reading on these boards, I have come to believe that it is a born-again Christian belief that you can be &quot;saved&quot; and have a spot in heaven no matter what you do on earth, no matter what atrocities you commit, because you have accepted Christ.  If this is true, than my &quot;hypothesis&quot; that religion is a way to keep us more human than animal is incorrect.  Furthermore, I fear that beliefs like these can give people free reign to commit horrible crimes against humanity (ie, murder, rape, genocide, molestation, and just plain rudeness to your fellow man and woman). <br>
<br>
Another thought...the phrase &quot;born-again&quot; in my mind connotes the idea that &quot;unchristian&quot; behavior preceded the &quot;renaissance.&quot;  Question:  Could this belief be an easy way for &quot;unchristian&quot; behavior (past and/or present) to be easily shrugged off.<br>
<br>
What do you think? <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#b9a1d0><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub98.ezboard.com/breligiousdebate60574.showUserPublicProfile?gid=rhinosmom>rhinosmom</A>&nbsp; <IMG SRC="http://mjkingbird.homestead.com/files/paige.gif" BORDER=0></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Member</span><br>  Posts: 154<br> <font color=#3333ff>(1/11/03 1:03 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub98.ezboard.com/freligiousdebate60574frm2.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=60.topic&index=1>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title>   Re: Saved, but at what cost?</span><hr size=1> Hmmm.....I don't think that religion is out there just to control people. But, I also think it's what one does with it and what they are really like.<br>
<br>
I wasn't raised with religion either. Never went to church as a kid, though my dad was raised Catholic.<br>
<br>
I found religion at 18. It suits me and I don't feel that it changed me really, well, not my personality I mean. It gave me peace and answers, etc. But I am still who I am.<br>
<br>
I have only heard this &quot;saved&quot; stuff from Born-Again Christians. I know why they are called that, but aren't all Christians born again at some point? The idea of my baptism was to start fresh, make a commitment, etc. Part of immersion baptism's symbolism is when you rise out of the water, it's like being born I guess.<br>
