<br>
1. God is all loving, all knowing and all powerful<br>
2. God created us (in his image)<br>
3. God created the law (which is perfect)<br>
4. God gave us free will so we have a choice whether to love him, follow his law etc. because what fun would it be if we were &quot;automatons.&quot;<br>
5a. We need to meet a standard of &quot;perfection&quot; in order to be with god.<br>
5b. Failing to meet that standard means we get cast into a lake of fire for all eternity.<br>
<br>
Am I right on the theory so far?<br>
Here is where it loses me completely:<br>
<br>
&quot;All have sinned and fall short of the law&quot;<br>
<br>
6a. In other words, we can never meet god's standard of perfection on our own because...<br>
<br>
6b. God made us SO WEAK/FLAWED that we can never succeed in following his laws or meeting his standard of perfection - so we require interventive salvation through Christ's death.<br>
<br>
OR<br>
<br>
6c. God made the laws SO DIFFICULT that no matter how we try we cannot succeed in following them all or meeting his standard of perfection - so we require interventive salvation through Christ's death.<br>
<br>
QUESTION 1: If God is all loving, all knowing and all powerful, why didn't he make his laws easier to follow or make us less flawed? Even if I believe I HAVE followed all of his laws - then I have just committed the sin of PRIDE and am still fall short of his ideal. It's a no-win setup.<br>
<br>
Enter Christ. All you have to do is believe that some 2000 years ago, Jesus was born of a virgin, preached love and forgiveness and scolded some pharisees, never sinned, was crucified, died and rose from the dead three days later, then disappeared from the face of the earth and is sitting at god's right hand, and in fact IS god as part of the trinity of HF+HS+JC. And if you just BELIEVE this, your past and future sins will be forgiven by god and you can be with god, plus you get eternal life in heaven instead of the lake of fire. Oh, and all this is &quot;god's perfect plan for salvation.&quot;<br>
<br>
QUESTION 2: What is perfect about this plan which is-<br>
a. difficult to believe<br>
b. has an innocent punished for our &quot;sins&quot;<br>
c. assumes typical human behavior is sinful and abhorrent to the perfect god who created is his image<br>
d. assumes that no matter how good we try to be, we will never be satisfactory to god without also believing &quot;Christ died for our sins.&quot;<br>
<br>
And now, a little analogy:<br>
<br>
